    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Looking Forward, Now and Then</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By Frances Anderton</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Anderton, Frances</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Futuristic buildings in Culver City area of Los Angeles is open for tour (Currents); photo (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Futuristic buildings with names like Backslash and Stealth (above) have emerged in Culver City in the last decade. Designed by the architect Eric Owen Moss and occupied by high-tech and film production companies, the complex is open for a walking tour ($65) on Sunday as a fund-raiser for the MAK Center for Art and Architecture. Information: (323) 651-1510.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>Futuristic buildings with names like Backslash and Stealth (above) have emerged in Culver City in the last decade. Designed by the architect Eric Owen Moss and occupied by high-tech and film production companies, the complex is open for a walking tour ($65) on Sunday as a fund-raiser for the MAK Center for Art and Architecture. Information: (323) 651-1510.</p>
        <p>Also on Sunday, a chance to experience yesterday's futurism at a symposium on John Lautner's famous Silvertop House. At Silvertop; $45; information: (323) 951-1061. On Oct. 26 at the Italian Cultural Institute in Westwood, Frank Gehry and others celebrate the late Bruno Zevi, an Italian architect and critic who was a proponent of organic architecture. Mr. Zevi, who died this year, introduced Frank Lloyd Wright to Italians and later wrote extensively about Mr. Gehry; (310) 443-3250.</p>
        <p>CURRENTS: LOS ANGELES -- ARCHITECTURE</p>
      </block>
